Detailed Description

An Demand is an abstract description of an operation to be performed.

An Demand provides a facility for performing late runtime binding between the code in different applications. Its most significant use is in the launching of pages, where it can be thought of as the glue between pages. It is basically a passive data structure holding an abstract description of an action to be performed.

For information about how to create and resolve Demand, reference to Publisher.

 // Set action and int value to Demand
 Demand demand;
 demand.setAction("MY_TEST_ACTION");
 demand.putIntExtra(1000);

 // Use Demand to start Page
 Demand demand;
 demand.setClassName("PackageName", ".PageName");
 context.startPage(&Demand);

Enumerator:
FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION 

If set, the recipient of this Demand will be granted permission to perform read operations on the Uri in the Demand's data.

FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION 

If set, the recipient of this Demand will be granted permission to perform write operations on the Uri in the Demand's data.

FLAG_FROM_BACKGROUND 

Can be set by the caller to indicate that this Demand is coming from a background operation, not from direct user interaction.

FLAG_DEBUG_LOG_RESOLUTION 

A flag you can enable for debugging: when set, log messages will be printed during the resolution of this Demand to show you what has been found to create the final resolved list.

FLAG_PAGE_NO_HISTORY 

If set, the new Page is not kept in the history stack.

As soon as the user navigates away from it, the Page is finished.

FLAG_PAGE_SINGLE_TOP 

If set, the Page will not be launched if it is already running at the top of the history stack.

FLAG_PAGE_NEW_TASK 

If set, this Page will become the start of a new task on this history stack. A task (from the Page that started it to the next task Page) defines an atomic group of Pages that the user can move to. Tasks can be moved to the foreground and background; all of the Pages inside of a particular task always remain in the same order.

This flag is generally used by Pages that want to present a "launcher" style behavior: they give the user a list of separate things that can be done, which otherwise run completely independently of the Page launching them.

When using this flag, if a task is already running for the Page you are now starting, then a new Page will not be started; instead, the current task will simply be brought to the front of the screen with the state it was last in. See FLAG_PAGE_MULTIPLE_TASK for a flag to disable this behavior.

This flag can not be used when the caller is requesting a result from the Page being launched.

FLAG_PAGE_MULTIPLE_TASK 

Do not use this flag unless you are implementing your own top-level launcher. Used in conjunction with FLAG_PAGE_NEW_TASK to disable the behavior of bringing an existing task to the foreground. When set, a new task is always started to host the Page for the Demand, regardless of whether there is already an existing task running the same thing.

Because the default system does not include graphical task management, you should not use this flag unless you provide some way for a user to return back to the tasks you have launched.

This flag is ignored if FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK is not set.

FLAG_PAGE_CLEAR_TOP 

If set, and the Page being launched is already running in the current task, then instead of launching a new instance of that Page, all of the other Pages on top of it will be closed and this Demand will be delivered to the (now on top) old Page as a new Demand.

For example, consider a task consisting of the Pages: A, B, C, D. If D calls startPage() with an Demand that resolves to the component of Page B, then C and D will be finished and B receive the given Demand, resulting in the stack now being: A, B.

The currently running instance of Page B in the above example will either receive the new intent you are starting here in its onNewDemand() method, or be itself finished and restarted with the new Demand. If it has declared its launch mode to be "multiple" (the default) and you have not set FLAG_PAGE_SINGLE_TOP in the same Demand, then it will be finished and re-created; for all other launch modes or if FLAG_PAGE_SINGLE_TOP is set then this Demand will be delivered to the current instance's onNewDemand().

This launch mode can also be used to good effect in conjunction with FLAG_PAGE_NEW_TASK: if used to start the root Page of a task, it will bring any currently running instance of that task to the foreground, and then clear it to its root state. This is especially useful, for example, when launching an Page from the notification manager.

FLAG_PAGE_FORWARD_RESULT 

If set and this Demand is being used to launch a new Page from an existing one, then the reply target of the existing Page will be transfered to the new Page.

This way the new Page can call setResult() and have that result sent back to the reply target of the original Page.

FLAG_PAGE_PREVIOUS_IS_TOP 

If set and this Demand is being used to launch a new Page from an existing one, the current Page will not be counted as the top Page for deciding whether the new Demand should be delivered to the top instead of starting a new one.

The previous Page will be used as the top, with the assumption being that the current Page will finish itself immediately.

FLAG_PAGE_EXCLUDE_FROM_RECENTS 

If set, the new Page is not kept in the list of recently launched Pages.

FLAG_PAGE_BROUGHT_TO_FRONT 

This flag is not normally set by application code, but set for you by the system when launch mode is singleTask.

If, when starting the Page, there is already a task running that starts with this Page, then instead of starting a new instance the current task is brought to the front. The existing instance will receive a call to Page::onNewIntent() with the new Demand that is being started, and with the FLAG_ACTIVITY_BROUGHT_TO_FRONT flag set.

FLAG_PAGE_RESET_TASK_IF_NEEDED 

If set, and this Page is either being started in a new task or bringing to the top an existing task, then it will be launched as the front door of the task.

This will result in the application of any affinities needed to have that task in the proper state (either moving Pages to or from it), or simply resetting that task to its initial state if needed.

FLAG_PAGE_LAUNCHED_FROM_HISTORY 

This flag is not normally set by application code, but set for you by the system if this Page is being launched from history (long longpress home key).

FLAG_PAGE_CLEAR_WHEN_TASK_RESET 

If set, this marks a point in the task's Page stack that should be cleared when the task is reset. That is, the next time the task is brought to the foreground with FLAG_PAGE_RESET_TASK_IF_NEEDED (typically as a result of the user re-launching it from home), this Page and all on top of it will be finished so that the user does not return to them, but instead returns to whatever Page preceeded it.

This is useful for cases where you have a logical break in your application. For example, an e-mail application may have a command to view an attachment, which launches an image view Page to display it. This Page should be part of the e-mail application's task, since it is a part of the task the user is involved in. However, if the user leaves that task, and later selects the e-mail app from home, we may like them to return to the conversation they were viewing, not the picture attachment, since that is confusing. By setting this flag when launching the image viewer, that viewer and any Pages it starts will be removed the next time the user returns to mail.

FLAG_PAGE_NO_USER_ACTION 

If set, this flag will prevent the normal Page::onUserLeaveHint() callback from occurring on the current frontmost Page before it is paused as the newly-started Page is brought to the front.

Typically, an Page can rely on that callback to indicate that an explicit user action has caused their Page to be moved out of the foreground. The callback marks an appropriate point in the Page's lifecycle for it to dismiss any notifications that it intends to display "until the user has seen them," such as a blinking LED.

If an Page is ever started via any non-user-driven events such as phone-call receipt or an alarm handler, this flag should be passed to Context::startPage(), ensuring that the pausing Page does not think the user has acknowledged its notification.

FLAG_PAGE_REORDER_TO_FRONT 

If set in an Demand passed to Context::startPage(), this flag will cause the launched Page to be brought to the front of its task's history stack if it is already running.

For example, consider a task consisting of four Pages: A, B, C, D. If D calls startPage() with an Demand that resolves to the component of Page B, then B will be brought to the front of the history stack, with this resulting order: A, C, D, B.

This flag will be ignored if FLAG_PAGE_CLEAR_TOP is also specified.

FLAG_PAGE_NO_ANIMATION 

If set in an Demand passed to Context::startPage(), this flag will prevent the system from applying an Page transition animation to go to the next Page state.

This doesn't mean an animation will never run if another Page change happens that doesn't specify this flag before the Page started here is displayed, then that transition will be used. This this flag can be put to good use when you are going to do a series of Page operations but the animation seen by the user shouldn't be driven by the first Page change but rather a later one.

FLAG_PAGE_CLEAR_TASK 

If set in a Demand passed to Context::startPage(), this flag will cause any existing task that would be associated with the page to be cleared before the page is started.

That is, the page becomes the new root of an otherwise empty task, and any old pages are finished. This can only be used in conjunction with FLAG_PAGE_NEW_TASK.

FLAG_PAGE_TASK_ON_HOME 

If set in a Deamnd passed to startPage(), this flag will cause a newly launching task to be placed on top of the current home page task (if there is one).

That is, pressing back from the task will always return the user to home even if that was not the last page they saw. This can only be used in conjunction with FLAG_PAGE_NEW_TASK.

static Demand gaia::core::Demand::parseUri ( const gaia::base::String &  uri) [static]

Create a Demand from a URI.

This URI may encode the action, category, and other Demand fields, if it was returned by toUri(). If the Demand was not generate by toUri(), its data will be the entire URI and its action will be ACTION_VIEW.

The URI given here must not be relative -- that is, it must include the scheme and full path.

Parameters:
uriThe URI to turn into a Demand.
Returns:
Demand The newly created Demand object.

gaia::base::String gaia::core::Demand::toUri ( ) const

Convert this Demand into a String holding a URI representation of it.

The returned URI string has been properly URI encoded, so it can be used with Uri::parse(String). The URI contains the Demand's data as the base URI, with an additional fragment describing the action, categories, type, flags, package, component, and extras.

You can convert the returned string back to a Demand with parseUri(String).

Returns:
Returns a URI encoding URI string describing the entire contents of the Demand.
